# TikTok Dropship Automator — Cursor Rules

You are building a production-grade dropshipping automation platform. Follow these rules in every change.

## TypeScript

- Enable strict typing everywhere. Never use `any`; prefer `unknown` with type guards when types are uncertain.
- Define shared domain types in `src/types/` (e.g. `Product`, `Order`, `FulfillmentStatus`).
- Use Zod schemas at API boundaries to validate request/response payloads.
- Export explicit return types for service functions and API route handlers.

## Architecture

- Use Next.js 14+ App Router conventions: Server Components by default; `"use client"` only when needed.
- Keep API routes in `src/app/api/` — one concern per route file, thin handlers delegating to `src/lib/services/`.
- Business logic lives in `src/lib/services/`, not in React components or route handlers.
- Database access goes through Supabase client helpers in `src/lib/supabase/` (server vs browser clients separated).

## API Routes

- Always return typed JSON responses with consistent shape: `{ data }` on success, `{ error: { message, code? } }` on failure.
- Wrap handlers in try/catch; log errors server-side, return safe messages to clients.
- Validate HTTP method, auth session, and input before processing.
- Use idempotency keys for webhooks and order fulfillment to prevent duplicate processing.

## Security — CRITICAL

- **Never** expose API keys, encrypted credentials, or service-role Supabase keys to the client.
- Store secrets in environment variables (`OPENAI_API_KEY`, `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY`, etc.); reference via `process.env` only in server code.
- Encrypt user-provided API keys at rest before writing to `users` or `suppliers` tables.
- Verify TikTok webhook signatures before processing order events.
- Enforce Supabase Row Level Security — users may only access their own rows.
- Sanitize and validate all external URLs (supplier links, image URLs) before fetching.

## AI Layer

- Use structured outputs (JSON mode / tool calling) for title, description, and tag generation.
- Keep prompts in `src/lib/ai/prompts/` as versioned templates, not inline strings scattered in code.
- Track AI processing status on `products.status` and persist errors to `ai_processing_error`.

## Fulfillment

- Route orders only to suppliers with `supports_us_warehouse = true` to meet TikTok's 48-hour shipping SLA.
- Set `tiktok_deadline_at` on order creation and surface at-risk orders in the dashboard.
- Log every supplier API call in `fulfillment_attempts` for audit and retry logic.

## UI

- Use Tailwind CSS and shadcn/ui components. Match existing admin layout and sidebar patterns.
- Keep pages in `src/app/(admin)/` under the shared admin layout.
- Prefer accessible, semantic HTML; use Lucide icons consistently.

## Error Handling

- Fail gracefully with user-visible toasts/messages; never leak stack traces to the client.
- Retry transient failures (supplier API, OpenAI rate limits) with exponential backoff.
- Mark failed records explicitly in the database rather than silently dropping data.

## Testing & Quality

- Run `npm run lint` and `npm run build` before considering work complete.
- Add unit tests for service-layer logic; integration tests for critical API routes (webhooks, fulfillment).

## File Naming

- Components: PascalCase (`ProductCard.tsx`)
- Utilities/services: kebab-case or camelCase matching existing files (`product-service.ts`)
- API routes: RESTful paths (`/api/products`, `/api/webhooks/tiktok`)
